Introduction

This report was created to explain one single plot out of the group report.

1 The Violin Plot

As the data preparation part was covered in the previously mentioned report, we will show you the graph and will explain intricate features in the following sections. The graph can be seen below.

{
  
  age_min = (full_df$age - 0.5) %>% min() %>% as.factor()
  age_max = (full_df$age + 0.5) %>% max() %>% as.factor()

  age_min = rep(age_min, 5)
  age_max = rep(age_max, 5)
  
  y_min = c(0, 10, 12, 14, 16)
  y_max = c(y_min[2:5], 20)
  
  common_alpha = rep(0.4, 5)
  
  nstudents = full_df %>% 
     group_by(G3_d) %>% 
     summarise(n=n())
  
  y_text = (y_min + y_max)/2
  grades = c('F', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A')
  l_text = rep('', 5)
  for(i in 1:5) l_text[i] = glue::glue("{grades[i]}-students\n area ({nstudents$n[6-i]})")
  
  
  full_df %>% 
    ggplot() +
    annotate("rect",
             xmin = age_min, xmax = age_max,
             ymin = y_min,   ymax = y_max, 
             fill = colours_5[5:1],
             alpha = common_alpha
    ) +
    geom_split_violin(aes(x=age %>% as.factor(),  y=G3, fill=gender),
                      draw_quantiles = c(0.5)) +
    scale_fill_manual(values=alpha(c('#D3D3D3', '#808080'), 0.8)) +
    theme_bw() +
    annotate("text", x = "22", y = y_text,  label = l_text) +
    labs(x = "Age",
         y = "Final grade",
         title = "Comparison males and females' grades against age") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
  
}

Figure 1.1: Comparison males and females’ grades against age

This visual displays the distribution for each age and gender group. Abscissa corresponds to the age group, whereas ordinate is final grade. Also, different grade areas - from F-students area (red) to A-students area (green) are highlighted. Although, in the original report bar chart with student final grade distribution was presented, the number of students in each grade group was featured again as a number in the brackets.

2 Explanation part

2.1 What

This figure conveys a few important messages:

  • there is no difference between grades of males and females
  • two the biggest grade group are places in D and F areas
  • almost all the medians across age groups are in D area, except a few which are in C area

2.2 For whom

This particular visualization can be useful for heads of researched schools. Since it can allow them to track students’ grades and correct educational program to help students achieve a better scores in the future.

2.3 Why

This type of visualization was chosen due to the need to show the distributions for a lot of age and gender groups at the same time in a compact way. Unfortunately, there was not a big range for choice and any alternatives could be less representative. (dot plot, two violin plots, bar chart, histogram and etc.)

2.4 How

The rendering of the graph can be divided into two parts: background and foreground. At the beginning of this work a color convention was accepted which applies to the range of 5 and 9 categories and in the current case the range of 5 colors was used regarding to the grades areas.

The color choice for the gender groups was dictated during peer-review to reduce distraction on the colours.

2.4.1 Background

In the background were drawn colored rectangles and corresponding labels. However, their drawing required some data preparation:

  # rectangles
  age_min = (full_df$age - 0.5) %>% min() %>% as.factor()
  age_max = (full_df$age + 0.5) %>% max() %>% as.factor()

  age_min = rep(age_min, 5)
  age_max = rep(age_max, 5)
  
  y_min = c(0, 10, 12, 14, 16)
  y_max = c(y_min[2:5], 20)
  
  common_alpha = rep(0.4, 5)
  
  # labels
  nstudents = full_df %>% 
     group_by(G3_d) %>% 
     summarise(n=n())
  
  y_text = (y_min + y_max)/2
  grades = c('F', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A')
  l_text = rep('', 5)
  for(i in 1:5) l_text[i] = glue::glue("{grades[i]}-students\n area ({nstudents$n[6-i]})")

As ggplot2::annotate function can take a vector at once, we provided the vector to draw 5 rectangles and their labels. As can be seen horizontal margins age_min and age_max were taken a little wider than needed and after that were transformed to factor values, because later geom_split_violin will use factorized abciss axis. Then vertical margins age_min and age_max were chosen accordingly the second table from the group report. The value of alpha was chosen empirically so as the grid behind rectangles is seen.

The pipe is used to get the amount of students in each discrete grade group. Then positions for the labels were got via the mean between margins for each grade area. At the last two lines a vector of labels was gotten with a glue function.

2.4.2 Foreground

In the foreground the most important part is a violin plot itself, as the ggplot2 package does not have function geom_split_violin, so we have to create it or invent from the scratch. Luckily, we manage to find solution on stackoverflow:

{ # custom split violin, enhanced 2020.07.03
  GeomSplitViolin <- ggproto("GeomSplitViolin", 
                              GeomViolin,
   draw_group = function(self, data, ..., draw_quantiles = NULL) {
     # Original function by Jan Gleixner (@jan-glx)
     # Adjustments by Wouter van der Bijl (@Axeman) 
     # and Ilia Ozhmegov (@ElijahOzhmegov)
     data <- transform(data, xminv = x - violinwidth * (x - xmin), xmaxv = x + violinwidth * (xmax - x))
     grp  <- data[1, "group"]
     
     newdata <- plyr::arrange(transform(data, x = if (grp %% 2 == 1) xminv else xmaxv), if (grp %% 2 == 1) y else -y)
     newdata <- rbind(newdata[1, ], newdata, newdata[nrow(newdata), ], newdata[1, ])
     newdata[c(1, nrow(newdata) - 1, nrow(newdata)), "x"] <- round(newdata[1, "x"])
     
     if (length(draw_quantiles) > 0 & !scales::zero_range(range(data$y))) {
       stopifnot(all(draw_quantiles >= 0), all(draw_quantiles <= 1))
       quantiles  <- create_quantile_segment_frame(data, draw_quantiles, split = TRUE, grp = grp)
       aesthetics <- data[rep(1, nrow(quantiles)), setdiff(names(data), c("x", "y")), drop = FALSE]
       aesthetics$alpha <- rep(1, nrow(quantiles))
       both <- cbind(quantiles, aesthetics)
       quantile_grob <- GeomPath$draw_panel(both, ...)
       ggplot2:::ggname("geom_split_violin", grid::grobTree(GeomPolygon$draw_panel(newdata, ...), quantile_grob))
     }
     else {
       ggplot2:::ggname("geom_split_violin", GeomPolygon$draw_panel(newdata, ...))
     }
   }
   
  )
  
  create_quantile_segment_frame <- function(data, draw_quantiles, split = FALSE, grp = NULL) {
    dens <- cumsum(data$density) / sum(data$density)
    ecdf <- stats::approxfun(dens, data$y)
    ys <- ecdf(draw_quantiles)
    violin.xminvs <- (stats::approxfun(data$y, data$xminv))(ys)
    violin.xmaxvs <- (stats::approxfun(data$y, data$xmaxv))(ys)
    violin.xs <- (stats::approxfun(data$y, data$x))(ys)
    if (grp %% 2 == 0) {
      data.frame(
        x = ggplot2:::interleave(violin.xs, violin.xmaxvs),
        y = rep(ys, each = 2), group = rep(ys, each = 2)
      )
    } else {
      data.frame(
        x = ggplot2:::interleave(violin.xminvs, violin.xs),
        y = rep(ys, each = 2), group = rep(ys, each = 2)
      )
    }
  }
  
  geom_split_violin <- function(mapping = NULL, data = NULL, stat = "ydensity", position = "identity", ..., 
                                draw_quantiles = NULL, trim = TRUE, scale = "area", na.rm = FALSE, 
                                show.legend = NA, inherit.aes = TRUE) {
    layer(data = data, mapping = mapping, stat = stat, geom = GeomSplitViolin, position = position, 
          show.legend = show.legend, inherit.aes = inherit.aes, 
          params = list(trim = trim, scale = scale, draw_quantiles = draw_quantiles, na.rm = na.rm, ...))
  } 
}

First of all, let us express appreciation to Jan Gleixner (jan-glx) and Wouter van der Bijl (Axeman) for contribution in this work and providing the solution for geom_split_violin function.

As explanation only this single function will consume too much time, we will highlight only main points here: * GeomSplitViolin is responsible for drawing the violin plots * create_quantile_segment_frame is responsible for rendering quantile lines * geom_split_violin is a wrapper for both of them

2.4.3 Miscellaneous

  • scale_fill_manual is used to change a default colours to the grey ones.
  • theme_bw is used to change a default gray theme to the black and white one, because it looks better on white paper or white html page
  • labs is used to change x, y and title values to desired ones
  • theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) is used to make a title in the center above the plot (according to the accepted convention for titles in the work)
  • legend is placed outside of the plot not to overload more the graph
